17 f. destrictus ensis, etc.: the reference is to the familiar story of the sword of Damocles, told by Cic. Tusa. 5, 61. It here typifies the uneasy conscience and ever-pres- ent sear of death that threaten the wicked3 hence impia cervice—cui: equivalent to ei cml—Siculae: the Sicilians were proverbially luxu- rious, and the adjective is especially appropriate in connection with the reference to Damocles. Note that dapes is by its position contrasted with impia—‘ No rich banquets can offset the tyrant's wickedness.'
